**Addendum II:** Interview log

[[div class="blockquote"]]
**Interviewed:** Teacher Vincent Connor

**Interviewer:** Dr. Stein

**Foreword:** The following interview was conducted approximately two hours after the initial containment of Item 8536. Mr. Connor was visibly distressed throughout the interview.
-----
= **[BEGIN LOG]**

**Dr. Stein:** Please state your name and occupation for the record.

**Mr. Connor:** Vincent Connor. I-I'm a third-grade teacher at ████████ Primary School.

**Dr. Stein:** Thank you, Mr. Connor. Could you describe the events that led to your discovery?

**Mr. Connor:** I — yes. I noticed that a group of my students had been disappearing during recess for several days. Always the same six. I assumed they were just playing somewhere out of sight, but after the fourth or fifth day I decided to follow them.

//[Five seconds pause.]//

**Dr. Stein:** And where did they lead you?

**Mr. Connor:** To the old storage room at the back of the east wing. It hasn't been used in years — the door's supposed to be locked. I don't know how they got it open.

**Dr. Stein:** What did you find inside?

**Mr. Connor:** I found him. He was just... Standing there, in the middle room. The kids were around him, some reading a book and the others just talking to him. Very calm, all of them. I nearly had a heart-attack.

//[Mr. Connor pauses, adjusting his collar.]//

**Mr. Connor:** His eyes moved to me the moment I walked in. The kids didn't even flinch — they just looked up and said "Hey, Mr. Connor,  that's Mr. Watches!".

**Dr. Stein:** The children knew his name?

**Mr. Connor:** Apparently he'd told them. I asked them later how long they'd been visiting him, and they said since the first day they found the door open. They said he was kind. That he always made sure none of them got hurt, that he "watched over them" and made sure they arrived to their classes on time.

**Dr. Stein:** Can you describe their demeanor when they spoke about him?

**Mr. Connor:** Fond. Genuinely fond. A couple of them were upset when they realised he could barely move anymore. One of the girls said — and I'm quoting here — "He used to walk around a little at first, but now he just stands. We think he's tired."

//[A pause]//

**Dr. Stein:** What did you do after you found this "Mr. Watches"?

**Mr. Connor:** I told the kids to step outside and wait for me in the hall. Then I — I tried talking to him.

**Dr. Stein:** He responded?

**Mr. Connor:** Barely. His voice was very faint, like it took enormous effort. He said he meant no harm to the children. That he couldn't look after them properly anymore, not with his condition, his... curse. He asked me not to worry about him.

//[Mr. Connor is silent for a moment.]//

**Mr. Connor:** Then he asked me to turn the light off on my way out.

**Dr. Stein:** Did you comply?

**Mr. Connor:** I — yes. I gathered the kids and we left. I reached for the switch just outside the door, and that's when I heard it.

**Dr. Stein:** Heard what, Mr. Connor?

**Mr. Connor:** A whisper. From inside the room, after I'd already closed the door. It was him, Mr. Watches. He said...

//[Mr. Connor stops. He folds his hands on the table.]//

**Mr. Connor:** "Thank you..., but I'm still watching."

//[A long pause.]//

**Dr. Stein:** Are you alright, Mr. Connor?

**Mr. Connor:** I called the police from the parking lot. I don't — I don't know what else I was supposed to do.

= **[END LOG]**
-----
**Afterword:** Afterword: In the weeks following this interview, Mr. Connor submitted repeated reports of a persistent sensation of being observed, most frequently during periods of isolation at his private residence. [[footnote]] Mr. Connor had been administered Class-A amnestics prior to submitting these reports. [[/footnote]] Standard psychological counselling has been administered on a bi-monthly basis. All Facility 04 personnel presenting comparable symptoms are reminded that psychological support is available without restriction.

